# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bioinformatics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Computational, statistical, and computer programming techniques have been used for computer simulation analyses of biological queries.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] They include reused specific analysis "pipelines", particularly in the field of genomics, such as by the identification of genes and single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These pipelines are used to better understand the genetic basis of disease, unique adaptations, desirable properties (especially in agricultural species), or differences between populations.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics also includes proteomics, which aims to understand the organizational principles within nucleic acid and protein sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Image and signal processing allow the extraction of useful results from large amounts of raw data.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] It aids in sequencing and annotating genomes and their observed mutations.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics includes text mining of biological literature and the development of biological and gene ontologies to organize and query biological data.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] It also plays a role in the analysis of gene and protein expression and regulation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatic tools aid in comparing, analyzing, and interpreting genetic and genomic data and in the understanding of evolutionary aspects of molecular biology.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] At a more integrative level, it helps analyze and catalogue the biological pathways and networks that are an important part of systems biology.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In structural biology, it aids in the simulation and modeling of DNA, RNA, proteins as well as biomolecular interactions.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The first definition of the term *bioinformatics* was coined by Paulien Hogeweg and Ben Hesper in 1970, to refer to the study of information processes in biotic systems.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This definition placed bioinformatics as a field parallel to biochemistry (the study of chemical processes in biological systems).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics and computational biology involved the analysis of biological data, particularly DNA, RNA, and protein sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The field of bioinformatics experienced explosive growth starting in the mid-1990s, driven largely by the Human Genome Project and by rapid advances in DNA sequencing technology.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Analyzing biological data to produce meaningful information involves writing and running software programs that use algorithms from graph theory, artificial intelligence, soft computing, data mining, image processing, and computer simulation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The algorithms in turn depend on theoretical foundations such as discrete mathematics, control theory, system theory, information theory, and statistics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] There has been a tremendous advance in speed and cost reduction since the completion of the Human Genome Project, with some labs able to sequence over 100,000 billion bases each year, and a full genome can be sequenced for $1,000 or less.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Computers became essential in molecular biology when protein sequences became available after Frederick Sanger determined the sequence of insulin in the early 1950s.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Comparing multiple sequences manually turned out to be impractical.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Margaret Oakley Dayhoff, a pioneer in the field, compiled one of the first protein sequence databases, initially published as books as well as methods of sequence alignment and molecular evolution.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Another early contributor to bioinformatics was Elvin A.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Kabat, who pioneered biological sequence analysis in 1970 with his comprehensive volumes of antibody sequences released online with Tai Te Wu between 1980 and 1991.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In the 1970s, new techniques for sequencing DNA were applied to bacteriophage MS2 and øX174, and the extended nucleotide sequences were then parsed with informational and statistical algorithms.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These studies illustrated that well known features, such as the coding segments and the triplet code, are revealed in straightforward statistical analyses and were the proof of the concept that bioinformatics would be insightful.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In order to study how normal cellular activities are altered in different disease states, raw biological data must be combined to form a comprehensive picture of these activities.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Therefore, the field of bioinformatics has evolved such that the most pressing task now involves the analysis and interpretation of various types of data.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This also includes nucleotide and amino acid sequences, protein domains, and protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The primary goal of bioinformatics is to increase the understanding of biological processes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] What sets it apart from other approaches is its focus on developing and applying computationally intensive techniques to achieve this goal.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Examples include: pattern recognition, data mining, machine learning algorithms, and visualization.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics entails the creation and advancement of databases, algorithms, computational and statistical techniques, and theory to solve formal and practical problems arising from the management and analysis of biological data.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Over the past few decades, rapid developments in genomic and other molecular research technologies and developments in information technologies have combined to produce a tremendous amount of information related to molecular biology.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics is the name given to these mathematical and computing approaches used to glean understanding of biological processes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Common activities in bioinformatics include mapping and analyzing DNA and protein sequences, aligning DNA and protein sequences to compare them, and creating and viewing 3-D models of protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Since the bacteriophage Phage Φ-X174 was sequenced in 1977, the DNA sequences of thousands of organisms have been decoded and stored in databases.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This sequence information is analyzed to determine genes that encode proteins, RNA genes, regulatory sequences, structural motifs, and repetitive sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A comparison of genes within a species or between different species can show similarities between protein functions, or relations between species (the use of molecular systematics to construct phylogenetic trees).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] With the growing amount of data, it long ago became impractical to analyze DNA sequences manually.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Computer programs such as BLAST are used routinely to search sequences—as of 2008, from more than 260,000 organisms, containing over 190 billion nucleotides.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Before sequences can be analyzed, they are obtained from a data storage bank, such as GenBank.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] DNA sequencing is still a non-trivial problem as the raw data may be noisy or affected by weak signals.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Algorithms have been developed for base calling for the various experimental approaches to DNA sequencing.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Most DNA sequencing techniques produce short fragments of sequence that need to be assembled to obtain complete gene or genome sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The shotgun sequencing technique (used by The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) to sequence the first bacterial genome, *Haemophilus influenzae*) generates the sequences of many thousands of small DNA fragments (ranging from 35 to 900 nucleotides long, depending on the sequencing technology).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The ends of these fragments overlap and, when aligned properly by a genome assembly program, can be used to reconstruct the complete genome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Shotgun sequencing yields sequence data quickly, but the task of assembling the fragments can be quite complicated for larger genomes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For a genome as large as the human genome, it may take many days of CPU time on large-memory, multiprocessor computers to assemble the fragments, and the resulting assembly usually contains numerous gaps that must be filled in later.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Shotgun sequencing is the method of choice for virtually all genomes sequenced (rather than chain-termination or chemical degradation methods), and genome assembly algorithms are a critical area of bioinformatics research.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In genomics, annotation refers to the process of marking the stop and start regions of genes and other biological features in a sequenced DNA sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Many genomes are too large to be annotated by hand.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] As the rate of sequencing exceeds the rate of genome annotation, genome annotation has become the new bottleneck in bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Genome annotation can be classified into three levels: the nucleotide, protein, and process levels.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Gene finding is a chief aspect of nucleotide-level annotation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For complex genomes, a combination of ab initio gene prediction and sequence comparison with expressed sequence databases and other organisms can be successful.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Nucleotide-level annotation also allows the integration of genome sequence with other genetic and physical maps of the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The principal aim of protein-level annotation is to assign function to the protein products of the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Databases of protein sequences and functional domains and motifs are used for this type of annotation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] About half of the predicted proteins in a new genome sequence tend to have no obvious function.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Understanding the function of genes and their products in the context of cellular and organismal physiology is the goal of process-level annotation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] An obstacle of process-level annotation has been the inconsistency of terms used by different model systems.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The Gene Ontology Consortium is helping to solve this problem.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The first description of a comprehensive annotation system was published in 1995 by The Institute for Genomic Research, which performed the first complete sequencing and analysis of the genome of a free-living (non-symbiotic) organism, the bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The system identifies the genes encoding all proteins, transfer RNAs, ribosomal RNAs, in order to make initial functional assignments.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The GeneMark program trained to find protein-coding genes in *Haemophilus influenzae* is constantly changing and improving.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Following the goals that the Human Genome Project left to achieve after its closure in 2003, the ENCODE project was developed by the National Human Genome Research Institute.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] While genome annotation is primarily based on sequence similarity (and thus homology), other properties of sequences can be used to predict the function of genes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In fact, most *gene* function prediction methods focus on *protein* sequences as they are more informative and more feature-rich.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For instance, the distribution of hydrophobic amino acids predicts transmembrane segments in proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] However, protein function prediction can also use external information such as gene (or protein) expression data, protein structure, or protein–protein interactions.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Evolutionary biology is the study of the origin and descent of species, as well as their change over time.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The core of comparative genome analysis is the establishment of the correspondence between genes (orthology analysis) or other genomic features in different organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Intergenomic maps are made to trace the evolutionary processes responsible for the divergence of two genomes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A multitude of evolutionary events acting at various organizational levels shape genome evolution.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] At the lowest level, point mutations affect individual nucleotides.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] At a higher level, large chromosomal segments undergo duplication, lateral transfer, inversion, transposition, deletion and insertion.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Entire genomes are involved in processes of hybridization, polyploidization and endosymbiosis that lead to rapid speciation.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Many of these studies are based on the detection of sequence homology to assign sequences to protein families.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Pan genomics is a concept introduced in 2005 by Tettelin and Medini.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Pan genome is the complete gene repertoire of a particular monophyletic taxonomic group.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Although initially applied to closely related strains of a species, it can be applied to a larger context like genus, phylum, etc.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] It is divided in two parts: the Core genome, a set of genes common to all the genomes under study (often housekeeping genes vital for survival), and the Dispensable/Flexible genome: a set of genes not present in all but one or some genomes under study.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A bioinformatics tool BPGA can be used to characterize the Pan Genome of bacterial species.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] As of 2013, the existence of efficient high-throughput next-generation sequencing technology allows for the identification of cause many different human disorders.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Simple Mendelian inheritance has been observed for over 3,000 disorders that have been identified at the Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man database, but complex diseases are more difficult.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Association studies have found many individual genetic regions that individually are weakly associated with complex diseases (such as infertility, breast cancer and Alzheimer's disease), rather than a single cause.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] There are currently many challenges to using genes for diagnosis and treatment, such as how we don't know which genes are important, or how stable the choices an algorithm provides.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Genome-wide association studies have successfully identified thousands of common genetic variants for complex diseases and traits; however, these common variants only explain a small fraction of heritability.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Rare variants may account for some of the missing heritability.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Large-scale whole genome sequencing studies have rapidly sequenced millions of whole genomes, and such studies have identified hundreds of millions of rare variants.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Functional annotations predict the effect or function of a genetic variant and help to prioritize rare functional variants, and incorporating these annotations can effectively boost the power of genetic association of rare variants analysis of whole genome sequencing studies.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Some tools have been developed to provide all-in-one rare variant association analysis for whole-genome sequencing data, including integration of genotype data and their functional annotations, association analysis, result summary and visualization.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Meta-analysis of whole genome sequencing studies provides an attractive solution to the problem of collecting large sample sizes for discovering rare variants associated with complex phenotypes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In cancer, the genomes of affected cells are rearranged in complex or unpredictable ways.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In addition to single-nucleotide polymorphism arrays identifying point mutations that cause cancer, oligonucleotide microarrays can be used to identify chromosomal gains and losses (called comparative genomic hybridization).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These detection methods generate terabytes of data per experiment.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The data is often found to contain considerable variability, or noise, and thus Hidden Markov model and change-point analysis methods are being developed to infer real copy number changes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Two important principles can be used to identify cancer by mutations in the exome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] First, cancer is a disease of accumulated somatic mutations in genes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Second, cancer contains driver mutations which need to be distinguished from passengers.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Further improvements in bioinformatics could allow for classifying types of cancer by analysis of cancer driven mutations in the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Furthermore, tracking of patients while the disease progresses may be possible in the future with the sequence of cancer samples.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Another type of data that requires novel informatics development is the analysis of lesions found to be recurrent among many tumors.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] All of these techniques are extremely noise-prone and/or subject to bias in the biological measurement, and a major research area in computational biology involves developing statistical tools to separate signal from noise in high-throughput gene expression studies.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Such studies are often used to determine the genes implicated in a disorder: one might compare microarray data from cancerous epithelial cells to data from non-cancerous cells to determine the transcripts that are up-regulated and down-regulated in a particular population of cancer cells.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Protein microarrays and high throughput (HT) mass spectrometry (MS) can provide a snapshot of the proteins present in a biological sample.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Cellular protein localization in a tissue context can be achieved through affinity proteomics displayed as spatial data based on immunohistochemistry and tissue microarrays.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Gene regulation is a complex process where a signal, such as an extracellular signal such as a hormone, eventually leads to an increase or decrease in the activity of one or more proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics techniques have been applied to explore various steps in this process.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For example, gene expression can be regulated by nearby elements in the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Promoter analysis involves the identification and study of sequence motifs in the DNA surrounding the protein-coding region of a gene.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These motifs influence the extent to which that region is transcribed into mRNA.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Enhancer elements far away from the promoter can also regulate gene expression, through three-dimensional looping interactions.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These interactions can be determined by bioinformatic analysis of chromosome conformation capture experiments.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Expression data can be used to infer gene regulation: one might compare microarray data from a wide variety of states of an organism to form hypotheses about the genes involved in each state.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In a single-cell organism, one might compare stages of the cell cycle, along with various stress conditions (heat shock, starvation, etc.).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Clustering algorithms can be then applied to expression data to determine which genes are co-expressed.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For example, the upstream regions (promoters) of co-expressed genes can be searched for over-represented regulatory elements.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Examples of clustering algorithms applied in gene clustering are k-means clustering, self-organizing maps (SOMs), hierarchical clustering, and consensus clustering methods.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Several approaches have been developed to analyze the location of organelles, genes, proteins, and other components within cells.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A gene ontology category, *cellular component*, has been devised to capture subcellular localization in many biological databases.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Microscopic pictures allow for the location of organelles as well as molecules, which may be the source of abnormalities in diseases.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Finding the location of proteins allows us to predict what they do.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This is called protein function prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] For instance, if a protein is found in the nucleus it may be involved in gene regulation or splicing.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] By contrast, if a protein is found in mitochondria, it may be involved in respiration or other metabolic processes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] There are well developed protein subcellular localization prediction resources available, including protein subcellular location databases, and prediction tools.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Data from high-throughput chromosome conformation capture experiments, such as Hi-C (experiment) and ChIA-PET, can provide information on the three-dimensional structure and nuclear organization of chromatin.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Bioinformatic challenges in this field include partitioning the genome into domains, such as Topologically Associating Domains (TADs), that are organised together in three-dimensional space.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Finding the structure of proteins is an important application of bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The Critical Assessment of Protein Structure Prediction (CASP) is an open competition where worldwide research groups submit protein models for evaluating unknown protein models.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The linear amino acid sequence of a protein is called the primary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The primary structure can be easily determined from the sequence of codons on the DNA gene that codes for it.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In most proteins, the primary structure uniquely determines the 3-dimensional structure of a protein in its native environment.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] An exception is the misfolded prion protein involved in bovine spongiform encephalopathy.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This structure is linked to the function of the protein.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Additional structural information includes the *secondary*, *tertiary* and *quaternary* structure.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A viable general solution to the prediction of the function of a protein remains an open problem.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Most efforts have so far been directed towards heuristics that work most of the time.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In the genomic branch of bioinformatics, homology is used to predict the function of a gene: if the sequence of gene *A*, whose function is known, is homologous to the sequence of gene *B,* whose function is unknown, one could infer that B may share A's function.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In structural bioinformatics, homology is used to determine which parts of a protein are important in structure formation and interaction with other proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Homology modeling is used to predict the structure of an unknown protein from existing homologous proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] One example of this is hemoglobin in humans and the hemoglobin in legumes (leghemoglobin), which are distant relatives from the same protein superfamily.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Both serve the same purpose of transporting oxygen in the organism.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Although both of these proteins have very different amino acid sequences, their protein structures are very similar, reflecting their shared function and shared ancestor.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Other techniques for predicting protein structure include protein threading and *de novo* (from scratch) physics-based modeling.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Another aspect of structural bioinformatics include the use of protein structures for Virtual Screening models such as Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship models and proteochemometric models (PCM).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Furthermore, a protein's crystal structure can be used in simulation of for example ligand-binding studies and *in silico* mutagenesis studies.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A 2021 deep-learning algorithms-based software called AlphaFold, developed by Google's DeepMind, greatly outperforms all other prediction software methods, and has released predicted structures for hundreds of millions of proteins in the AlphaFold protein structure database.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A variety of methods have been developed to tackle the protein–protein docking problem, though it seems that there is still much work to be done in this field.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Other interactions encountered in the field include Protein–ligand (including drug) and protein–peptide.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Molecular dynamic simulation of movement of atoms about rotatable bonds is the fundamental principle behind computational algorithms, termed docking algorithms, for studying molecular interactions.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Biodiversity informatics deals with the collection and analysis of biodiversity data, such as taxonomic databases, or microbiome data.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Examples of such analyses include phylogenetics, niche modelling, species richness mapping, DNA barcoding, or species identification tools.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A growing area is also macro-ecology, i.e. the study of how biodiversity is connected to ecology and human impact, such as climate change.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The enormous number of published literature makes it virtually impossible for individuals to read every paper, resulting in disjointed sub-fields of research.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Literature analysis aims to employ computational and statistical linguistics to mine this growing library of text resources.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The area of research draws from statistics and computational linguistics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Computational technologies are used to automate the processing, quantification and analysis of large amounts of high-information-content biomedical imagery.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Modern image analysis systems can improve an observer's accuracy, objectivity, or speed.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Image analysis is important for both diagnostics and research.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Computational techniques are used to analyse high-throughput, low-measurement single cell data, such as that obtained from flow cytometry.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These methods typically involve finding populations of cells that are relevant to a particular disease state or experimental condition.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Biological ontologies are directed acyclic graphs of controlled vocabularies.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] They create categories for biological concepts and descriptions so they can be easily analyzed with computers.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] When categorised in this way, it is possible to gain added value from holistic and integrated analysis.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The OBO Foundry was an effort to standardise certain ontologies.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] One of the most widespread is the Gene ontology which describes gene function.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] There are also ontologies which describe phenotypes.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Databases are essential for bioinformatics research and applications.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Databases exist for many different information types, including DNA and protein sequences, molecular structures, phenotypes and biodiversity.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Databases can contain both empirical data (obtained directly from experiments) and predicted data (obtained from analysis of existing data).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] They may be specific to a particular organism, pathway or molecule of interest.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Alternatively, they can incorporate data compiled from multiple other databases.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Databases can have different formats, access mechanisms, and be public or private.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Software tools for bioinformatics include simple command-line tools, more complex graphical programs, and standalone web-services.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] They are made by bioinformatics companies or by public institutions.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Many free and open-source software tools have existed and continued to grow since the 1980s.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The open source tools often act as incubators of ideas, or community-supported plug-ins in commercial applications.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] They may also provide *de facto* standards and shared object models for assisting with the challenge of bioinformation integration.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Open-source bioinformatics software includes Bioconductor, BioPerl, Biopython, BioJava, BioJS, BioRuby, Bioclipse, EMBOSS, .NET Bio, Orange with its bioinformatics add-on, Apache Taverna, UGENE and GenoCAD.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The non-profit Open Bioinformatics Foundation and the annual Bioinformatics Open Source Conference promote open-source bioinformatics software.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] SOAP- and REST-based interfaces have been developed to allow client computers to use algorithms, data and computing resources from servers in other parts of the world.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The main advantage are that end users do not have to deal with software and database maintenance overheads.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Basic bioinformatics services are classified by the EBI into three categories: SSS (Sequence Search Services), MSA (Multiple Sequence Alignment), and BSA (Biological Sequence Analysis).
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] A bioinformatics workflow management system is a specialized form of a workflow management system designed specifically to compose and execute a series of computational or data manipulation steps, or a workflow, in a Bioinformatics application.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Some of the platforms giving this service: Galaxy, Kepler, Taverna, UGENE, Anduril, HIVE.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In 2014, the US Food and Drug Administration sponsored a conference held at the National Institutes of Health Bethesda Campus to discuss reproducibility in bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Over the next three years, a consortium of stakeholders met regularly to discuss what would become BioCompute paradigm.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] These stakeholders included representatives from government, industry, and academic entities.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] It was decided that the BioCompute paradigm would be in the form of digital 'lab notebooks' which allow for the reproducibility, replication, review, and reuse, of bioinformatics protocols.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This was proposed to enable greater continuity within a research group over the course of normal personnel flux while furthering the exchange of ideas between groups.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The US FDA funded this work so that information on pipelines would be more transparent and accessible to their regulatory staff.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] In 2016, the group reconvened at the NIH in Bethesda and discussed the potential for a BioCompute Object, an instance of the BioCompute paradigm.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] This work was copied as both a "standard trial use" document and a preprint paper uploaded to bioRxiv.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The BioCompute object allows for the JSON-ized record to be shared among employees, collaborators, and regulators.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] While bioinformatics is taught as an in-person master's degree at many universities, there are many other methods and technologies available to learn and obtain certification in the subject.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The computational nature of bioinformatics lends it to computer-aided and online learning.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Software platforms designed to teach bioinformatics concepts and methods include Rosalind and online courses offered through the Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics Training Portal.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The Canadian Bioinformatics Workshops provides videos and slides from training workshops on their website under a Creative Commons license.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The 4273π project or 4273pi project also offers open source educational materials for free.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] The course runs on low cost Raspberry Pi computers and has been used to teach adults and school pupils.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] 4273 is actively developed by a consortium of academics and research staff who have run research level bioinformatics using Raspberry Pi computers and the 4273π operating system.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] There are several large conferences that are concerned with bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/bioinformatics] Some of the most notable examples are European Conference on Computational Biology (ECCB), Intelligent Systems for Molecular Biology (ISMB), Pacific Symposium on Biocomputing (PSB), and Research in Computational Molecular Biology (RECOMB).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] In bioinformatics, **BLAST** (**basic local alignment search tool**) is an algorithm and program for comparing primary biological sequence information, such as the amino-acid sequences of proteins , nucleotides of DNA and/or RNA sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] A BLAST search enables a researcher to compare a subject protein or nucleotide sequence (called a query) with a library or database of sequences, and identify database sequences that resemble the query sequence above a certain threshold.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For example, following the discovery of a previously unknown gene in the mouse, a scientist will typically perform a BLAST search of the human genome to see if humans carry a similar gene; BLAST will identify sequences in the human genome that resemble the mouse gene based on similarity of sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is a widely used bioinformatics programs for sequence searching.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] It addresses a fundamental problem in bioinformatics research.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm it uses is faster for large-scale searches compared to methods like Smith-Waterman.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This emphasis on speed is vital to making the algorithm practical on the huge genome databases currently available, although subsequent algorithms can be even faster.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The BLAST program was designed by Eugene Myers, Stephen Altschul, Warren Gish, David J.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Lipman and Webb Miller at the NIH and was published in J.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST builds upon FASTA, a previously developed program for protein and DNA sequence similarity searches.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] It incorporates a novel stochastic model developed by Samuel Karlin and Stephen Altschul.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST is faster than any Smith-Waterman implementation for most cases, it cannot "guarantee the optimal alignments of the query and database sequences" as Smith-Waterman algorithm does.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman algorithm was an extension of a previous optimal method, the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which was the first sequence alignment algorithm that was guaranteed to find the best possible alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, the time and space requirements of these optimal algorithms far exceed the requirements of BLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is more time-efficient than FASTA by searching only for the more significant patterns in the sequences, yet with comparative sensitivity.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This could be further realized by understanding the algorithm of BLAST introduced below.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is also often used as part of other algorithms that require approximate sequence matching.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is available on the web on the NCBI website.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Different types of BLASTs are available according to the query sequences and the target databases.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Alternative implementations include AB-BLAST (formerly known as WU-BLAST), FSA-BLAST (last updated in 2006), and ScalaBLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The original paper by Altschul, *et al.* was the most highly cited paper published in the 1990s.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences (in FASTA or Genbank format), database to search and other optional parameters such as scoring matrix.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST output can be delivered in a variety of formats.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] These formats include HTML, plain text, and XML formatting.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For NCBI's webpage, the default format for output is HTML.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] When performing a BLAST on NCBI, the results are given in a graphical format showing the hits found, a table showing sequence identifiers for the hits with scoring related data, as well as alignments for the sequence of interest and the hits received with corresponding BLAST scores for these.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The easiest to read and most informative of these is probably the table.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] If one is attempting to search for a proprietary sequence or simply one that is unavailable in databases available to the general public through sources such as NCBI, there is a BLAST program available for download to any computer, at no cost.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This can be found at BLAST+ executables.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] There are also commercial programs available for purchase.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Databases can be found on the NCBI site, as well as on the Index of BLAST databases (FTP).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Using a heuristic method, BLAST finds similar sequences, by locating short matches between the two sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This process of finding similar sequences is called seeding.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] It is after this first match that BLAST begins to make local alignments.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] While attempting to find similarity in sequences, sets of common letters, known as words, are very important.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For example, suppose that the sequence contains the following stretch of letters, GLKFA.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] If a BLAST was being conducted under normal conditions, the word size would be 3 letters.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] In this case, using the given stretch of letters, the searched words would be GLK, LKF, and KFA.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm of BLAST locates all common three-letter words between the sequence of interest and the hit sequence or sequences from the database.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This result will then be used to build an alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] After making words for the sequence of interest, the rest of the words are also assembled.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] These words must satisfy a requirement of having a score of at least the threshold *T*, when compared by using a scoring matrix.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] One commonly used scoring matrix for BLAST searches is BLOSUM62, although the optimal scoring matrix depends on sequence similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Once both words and neighborhood words are assembled and compiled, they are compared to the sequences in the database in order to find matches.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The threshold score *T* determines whether or not a particular word will be included in the alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Once seeding has been conducted, the alignment which is only 3 residues long, is extended in both directions by the algorithm used by BLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Each extension impacts the score of the alignment by either increasing or decreasing it.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] If this score is higher than a pre-determined *T*, the alignment will be included in the results given by BLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, if this score is lower than this pre-determined *T*, the alignment will cease to extend, preventing the areas of poor alignment from being included in the BLAST results.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] To run the software, BLAST requires a query sequence to search for, and a sequence to search against (also called the target sequence) or a sequence database containing multiple such sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST will find sub-sequences in the database which are similar to subsequences in the query.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] In typical usage, the query sequence is much smaller than the database, e.g., the query may be one thousand nucleotides while the database is several billion nucleotides.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The main idea of BLAST is that there are often High-scoring Segment Pairs (HSP) contained in a statistically significant alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST searches for high scoring sequence alignments between the query sequence and the existing sequences in the database using a heuristic approach that approximates the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, the exhaustive Smith-Waterman approach is too slow for searching large genomic databases such as GenBank.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, the BLAST algorithm uses a heuristic approach that is less accurate than the Smith-Waterman algorithm but over 50 times faster.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The speed and relatively good accuracy of BLAST are among the technical innovations of the BLAST programs.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Key steps of the algorithm include filtering low-complexity regions, identifying high-scoring word matches, and statistically evaluating alignments.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *Make a*k*-letter word list of the query sequence.* Take *k*=3 for example, we list the words of length 3 in the query protein sequence (*k* is usually 11 for a DNA sequence) "sequentially", until the last letter of the query sequence is included.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *List the possible matching words.* This step is one of the main differences between BLAST and FASTA.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] FASTA cares about all of the common words in the database and query sequences that are listed in step 2; however, BLAST only cares about the high-scoring words.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The scores are created by comparing the word in the list in step 2 with all the 3-letter words.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] By using the scoring matrix (substitution matrix) to score the comparison of each residue pair, there are 20^3 possible match scores for a 3-letter word.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For example, the score obtained by comparing PQG with PEG and PQA is respectively 15 and 12 with the BLOSUM62 weighting scheme.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For DNA words, a match is scored as +5 and a mismatch as -4, or as +2 and -3.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] After that, a neighborhood word score threshold *T* is used to reduce the number of possible matching words.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The words whose scores are greater than the threshold *T* will remain in the possible matching words list, while those with lower scores will be discarded.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For example, PEG is kept, but PQA is abandoned when T is 13.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *Organize the remaining high-scoring words into an efficient search tree.* This allows the program to rapidly compare the high-scoring words to the database sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *Scan the database sequences for exact matches with the remaining high-scoring words.* The BLAST program scans the database sequences for the remaining high-scoring word, such as PEG, of each position.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] If an exact match is found, this match is used to seed a possible un-gapped alignment between the query and database sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *List all of the HSPs in the database whose score is high enough to be considered.* We list the HSPs whose scores are greater than the empirically determined cutoff score *S*.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] By examining the distribution of the alignment scores modeled by comparing random sequences, a cutoff score *S* can be determined such that its value is large enough to guarantee the significance of the remaining HSPs.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *Evaluate the significance of the HSP score.* BLAST next assesses the statistical significance of each HSP score by exploiting the Gumbel extreme value distribution (EVD).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] (It is proved that the distribution of Smith-Waterman local alignment scores between two random sequences follows the Gumbel EVD.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For local alignments containing gaps it is not proved.).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Note that $\lambda$ and $\mathrm {K}$ depend upon the substitution matrix, gap penalties, and sequence composition (the letter frequencies). $m'$ and $n'$ are the effective lengths of the query and database sequences, respectively.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The original sequence length is shortened to the effective length to compensate for the edge effect (an alignment start near the end of one of the query or database sequence is likely not to have enough sequence to build an optimal alignment).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] They can be calculated as $m'\approx m-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ $n'\approx n-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ where $\mathrm {H}$ is the average expected score per aligned pair of residues in an alignment of two random sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Altschul and Gish gave the typical values, $\lambda =0.318$ , $\mathrm {K} =0.13$ , and $\mathrm {H} =0.40$ , for un-gapped local alignment using BLOSUM62 as the substitution matrix.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Using the typical values for assessing the significance is called the lookup table method; it is not accurate.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The expect score *E* of a database match is the number of times that an unrelated database sequence would obtain a score *S* higher than *x* by chance.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The calculation shown here is modified if individual HSPs are combined, such as when producing gapped alignments (described below), due to the variation of the statistical parameters.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] *Make two or more HSP regions into a longer alignment.* Sometimes, we find two or more HSP regions in one database sequence that can be made into a longer alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This provides additional evidence of the relation between the query and database sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] There are two methods, the Poisson method and the sum-of-scores method, to compare the significance of the newly combined HSP regions.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Suppose that there are two combined HSP regions with the pairs of scores (65, 40) and (52, 45), respectively.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The Poisson method gives more significance to the set with the maximal lower score (45>40).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, the sum-of-scores method prefers the first set, because 65+40 (105) is greater than 52+45(97).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The original BLAST uses the Poisson method; gapped BLAST and the WU-BLAST uses the sum-of scores method.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLASTn offers nucleotide to nucelotide searches.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when trying to identify evolutionary relationships between organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] tBLASTn used to carry out protein to translated DNA searches.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when looking for similar protein-coding regions in DNA sequences that haven't been fully annotated, like ESTs (short, single-read cDNA sequences) and HTGs (draft genome sequences).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Since these sequences don't have known protein translations, we can only search for them using tBLASTn.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx compares a nucleotide query sequence (can be translated into six different protein sequences) against a protein database.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This tool is useful when the reading frame of the DNA sequence is uncertain or contains errors that might cause mistakes in protein-coding.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx provides combined statistics for hits across all frames, making it helpful for the initial analysis of new DNA sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLASTp, or Protein BLAST, is used to compare protein sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] You can input one or more protein sequences that you want to compare against a single protein sequence or a database of protein sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when you're trying to identify a protein by finding similar sequences in existing protein databases.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Parallel BLAST versions of split databases are implemented using MPI and Pthreads, and have been ported to various platforms including Windows, Linux, Solaris, Mac OS X, and AIX.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Popular approaches to parallelize BLAST include query distribution, hash table segmentation, computation parallelization, and database segmentation (partition).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Databases are split into equal sized pieces and stored locally on each node.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Each query is run on all nodes in parallel and the resultant BLAST output files from all nodes merged to yield the final output.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Specific implementations include MPIblast, ScalaBLAST, DCBLAST and so on.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast makes use of a database segmentation technique to parallelize the computation process.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This allows for significant performance improvements when conducting BLAST searches across a set of nodes in a cluster.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] In some scenarios a superlinear speedup is achievable.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This makes MPIblast suitable for the extensive genomic datasets that are typically used in bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST generally runs at a speed of O(n), where n is the size of the database.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The time to complete the search increases linearly as the size of the database increases.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast utilizes parallel processing to speed up the search.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The ideal speed for any parallel computation is a complexity of O(n/p), with n being the size of the database and p being the number of processors.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This would indicate that the job is evenly distributed among the p number of processors.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This is visualized in the included graph.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The superlinear speedup that can sometimes occur with MPIblast can have a complexity better than O(n/p).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This occurs because the cache memory can be used to decrease the run time.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The predecessor to BLAST, FASTA, can also be used for protein and DNA similarity searching.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] FASTA provides a similar set of programs for comparing proteins to protein and DNA databases, DNA to DNA and protein databases, and includes additional programs for working with unordered short peptides and DNA sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] In addition, the FASTA package provides SSEARCH, a vectorized implementation of the rigorous Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] FASTA is slower than BLAST, but provides a much wider range of scoring matrices, making it easier to tailor a search to a specific evolutionary distance.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] An extremely fast but considerably less sensitive alternative to BLAST is BLAT (*B*last *L*ike *A*lignment *T*ool).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST does a linear search, BLAT relies on k-mer indexing the database, and can thus often find seeds faster.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Another software alternative similar to BLAT is PatternHunter.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Advances in sequencing technology in the late 2000s has made searching for very similar nucleotide matches an important problem.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] New alignment programs tailored for this use typically use BWT-indexing of the target database (typically a genome).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences can then be mapped very quickly, and output is typically in the form of a BAM file.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Example alignment programs are BWA, SOAP, and Bowtie.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For protein identification, searching for known domains (for instance from Pfam) by matching with Hidden Markov Models is a popular alternative, such as HMMER.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] An alternative to BLAST for comparing two banks of sequences is PLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] PLAST provides a high-performance general purpose bank to bank sequence similarity search tool relying on the PLAST and ORIS algorithms.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Results of PLAST are very similar to BLAST, but PLAST is significantly faster and capable of comparing large sets of sequences with a small memory (i.e.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For applications in metagenomics, where the task is to compare billions of short DNA reads against tens of millions of protein references, DIAMOND runs at up to 20,000 times as fast as BLASTX, while maintaining a high level of sensitivity.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The open-source software MMseqs is an alternative to BLAST/PSI-BLAST, which improves on current search tools over the full range of speed-sensitivity trade-off, achieving sensitivities better than PSI-BLAST at more than 400 times its speed.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] OptCAM is an example of such approaches and is shown to be faster than BLAST.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] While both Smith-Waterman and BLAST are used to find homologous sequences by searching and comparing a query sequence with those in the databases, they do have their differences.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Due to the fact that BLAST is based on a heuristic algorithm, the results received through BLAST will not include all the possible hits within the database.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] An alternative in order to find all the possible hits would be to use the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This method varies from the BLAST method in two areas, accuracy and speed.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman option provides better accuracy, in that it finds matches that BLAST cannot, because it does not exclude any information.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, it is necessary for remote homology.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, when compared to BLAST, it is more time consuming and requires large amounts of computing power and memory.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] However, advances have been made to speed up the Smith-Waterman search process dramatically.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] These advances include FPGA chips and SIMD technology.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] For more complete results from BLAST, the settings can be changed from their default settings.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The optimal settings for a given sequence, however, may vary.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] The settings one can change are E-Value, gap costs, filters, word size, and substitution matrix.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Note, the algorithm used for BLAST was developed from the algorithm used for Smith-Waterman.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST employs an alignment which finds "local alignments between sequences by finding short matches and from these initial matches (local) alignments are created".
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] To help users interpreting BLAST results, different software is available.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Example visualizations of BLAST results are shown in Figure 4 and 5.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] These include identifying species, locating domains, establishing phylogeny, DNA mapping, and comparison.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] With the use of BLAST, you can possibly correctly identify a species or find homologous species.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] This can be useful, for example, when you are working with a DNA sequence from an unknown species.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] Using the results received through BLAST you can create a phylogenetic tree using the BLAST web-page.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] methods, so should only be relied upon for "first pass" phylogenetic analyses.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] When working with a known species, and looking to sequence a gene at an unknown location, BLAST can compare the chromosomal position of the sequence of interest, to relevant sequences in the database(s).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] NCBI has a "Magic-BLAST" tool built around BLAST for this purpose.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] When working with genes, BLAST can locate common genes in two related species, and can be used to map annotations from one organism to another.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] BLAST can use genetic sequences to compare multiple taxa against known taxonomical data.
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] By doing this, it can provide a picture of the evolutionary relationships between various species (Fig.6).
[src:bioinformatics/blast-biotechnology] , since if the gene shows up in an organism outside of the ancestral lineage, then it wouldn't be classified as an orphan gene.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] In bioinformatics and biochemistry, the **FASTA format** is a text-based format for representing either nucleotide sequences or amino acid (protein) sequences, in which nucleotides or amino acids are represented using single-letter codes.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The format allows for sequence names and comments to precede the sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] It originated from the FASTA software package and has since become a near-universal standard in bioinformatics.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The simplicity of FASTA format makes it easy to manipulate and parse sequences using text-processing tools and scripting languages.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A sequence begins with a greater-than character (">") followed by a description of the sequence (all in a single line).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The lines immediately following the description line are the sequence representation, with one letter per amino acid or nucleic acid, and are typically no more than 80 characters in length.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The original FASTA/Pearson format is described in the documentation for the FASTA suite of programs.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] It can be downloaded with any free distribution of FASTA (see fasta20.doc, fastaVN.doc, or fastaVN.me—where VN is the Version Number).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] In the original format, a sequence was represented as a series of lines, each of which was no longer than 120 characters and usually did not exceed 80 characters.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] This probably was to allow for the preallocation of fixed line sizes in software: at the time most users relied on Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) VT220 (or compatible) terminals which could display 80 or 132 characters per line.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Most people preferred the bigger font in 80-character modes and so it became the recommended fashion to use 80 characters or less (often 70) in FASTA lines.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Also, the width of a standard printed page is 70 to 80 characters (depending on the font).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The first line in a FASTA file started either with a ">" (greater-than) symbol or, less frequently, a ";" (semicolon) was taken as a comment.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Subsequent lines starting with a semicolon would be ignored by software.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Following the initial line (used for a unique description of the sequence) was the actual sequence itself in the standard one-letter character string.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Anything other than a valid character would be ignored (including spaces, tabulators, asterisks, etc...).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] It was also common to end the sequence with an "*" (asterisk) character (in analogy with use in PIR formatted sequences) and, for the same reason, to leave a blank line between the description and the sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A multiple-sequence FASTA format, or multi-FASTA format, would be obtained by concatenating several single-sequence FASTA files in one file.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Thus, the examples above would be a multi-FASTA file if taken together.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Modern bioinformatics programs that rely on the FASTA format expect the sequence headers to be preceded by ">".
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The sequence is generally represented as "interleaved", or on multiple lines as in the above example, but may also be "sequential", or on a single line.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Running different bioinformatics programs may require conversions between "sequential" and "interleaved" FASTA formats.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The description line (defline) or header/identifier line, which begins with ">", gives a name and/or a unique identifier for the sequence, and may also contain additional information.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] In a deprecated practice, the header line sometimes contained more than one header, separated by a ^A (Control-A) character.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] In the original Pearson FASTA format, one or more comments, distinguished by a semi-colon at the beginning of the line, may occur after the header.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Some databases and bioinformatics applications do not recognize these comments and follow the NCBI FASTA specification.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The NCBI defined a standard for the unique identifier used for the sequence (SeqID) in the header line.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] This allows a sequence that was obtained from a database to be labelled with a reference to its database record.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The database identifier format is understood by the NCBI tools like `makeblastdb` and `table2asn`.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The following list describes the NCBI FASTA defined format for sequence identifiers.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The vertical bars ("|") in the above list are not separators in the sense of the Backus–Naur form but are part of the format.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Multiple identifiers can be concatenated, also separated by vertical bars.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Following the header line, the actual sequence is represented.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Sequences may be protein sequences or nucleic acid sequences, and they can contain gaps or alignment characters (see sequence alignment).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Numerical digits are not allowed but are used in some databases to indicate the position in the sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] There is no standard filename extension for a text file containing FASTA formatted sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The table below shows each extension and its respective meaning.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] FASTQ format is a form of FASTA format extended to indicate information related to sequencing.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] It is created by the Sanger Centre in Cambridge.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A2M/A3M are a family of FASTA-derived formats used for sequence alignments.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] In A2M/A3M sequences, lowercase characters are taken to mean insertions, which are then indicated in the other sequences as the dot (".") character.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] The dots can be discarded for compactness without loss of information.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] As with typical FASTA files used in alignments, the gap ("-") is taken to mean exactly one position.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A3M is similar to A2M, with the added rule that gaps aligned to insertions can too be discarded.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A plethora of user-friendly scripts are available from the community to perform FASTA file manipulations.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Online toolboxes, such as FaBox or the FASTX-Toolkit within Galaxy servers, are also available.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] These can be used to segregate sequence headers/identifiers, rename them, shorten them, or extract sequences of interest from large FASTA files based on a list of wanted identifiers (among other available functions).
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] A tree-based approach to sorting multi-FASTA files (TREE2FASTA) also exists based on the coloring and/or annotation of sequences of interest in the FigTree viewer.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Additionally, the Bioconductor *Biostrings* package can be used to read and manipulate FASTA files in R.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] Several online format converters exist to rapidly reformat multi-FASTA files to different formats (e.g.
[src:bioinformatics/fasta-format] NEXUS, PHYLIP) for use with different phylogenetic programs, such as the converter available on phylogeny.fr.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In computational biology, **gene prediction** or **gene finding** refers to the process of identifying the regions of genomic DNA that encode genes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This includes protein-coding genes as well as RNA genes, but may also include prediction of other functional elements such as regulatory regions.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Gene finding is one of the first and most important steps in understanding the genome of a species once it has been sequenced.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In its earliest days, "gene finding" was based on painstaking experimentation on living cells and organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Statistical analysis of the rates of homologous recombination of several different genes could determine their order on a certain chromosome, and information from many such experiments could be combined to create a genetic map specifying the rough location of known genes relative to each other.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Today, with comprehensive genome sequence and powerful computational resources at the disposal of the research community, gene finding has been redefined as a largely computational problem.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Determining that a sequence is functional should be distinguished from determining the function of the gene or its product.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Gene prediction is one of the key steps in genome annotation, following sequence assembly, the filtering of non-coding regions and repeat masking.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Gene prediction is closely related to the so-called 'target search problem' investigating how DNA-binding proteins (transcription factors) locate specific binding sites within the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In empirical (similarity, homology or evidence-based) gene finding systems, the target genome is searched for sequences that are similar to extrinsic evidence in the form of the known expressed sequence tags, messenger RNA (mRNA), protein products, and homologous or orthologous sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Given an mRNA sequence, it is trivial to derive a unique genomic DNA sequence from which it had to have been transcribed.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Given a protein sequence, a family of possible coding DNA sequences can be derived by reverse translation of the genetic code.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Once candidate DNA sequences have been determined, it is a relatively straightforward algorithmic problem to efficiently search a target genome for matches, complete or partial, and exact or inexact.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Given a sequence, local alignment algorithms such as BLAST, FASTA and Smith-Waterman look for regions of similarity between the target sequence and possible candidate matches.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Matches can be complete or partial, and exact or inexact.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The success of this approach is limited by the contents and accuracy of the sequence database.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] A high degree of similarity to a known messenger RNA or protein product is strong evidence that a region of a target genome is a protein-coding gene.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] However, to apply this approach systemically requires extensive sequencing of mRNA and protein products.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Not only is this expensive, but in complex organisms, only a subset of all genes in the organism's genome are expressed at any given time, meaning that extrinsic evidence for many genes is not readily accessible in any single cell culture.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Thus, to collect extrinsic evidence for most or all of the genes in a complex organism requires the study of many hundreds or thousands of cell types, which presents further difficulties.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] For example, some human genes may be expressed only during development as an embryo or fetus, which might be difficult to study for ethical reasons.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Despite these difficulties, extensive transcript and protein sequence databases have been generated for human as well as other important model organisms in biology, such as mice and yeast.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] For example, the RefSeq database contains transcript and protein sequence from many different species, and the Ensembl system comprehensively maps this evidence to human and several other genomes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] It is, however, likely that these databases are both incomplete and contain small but significant amounts of erroneous data.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Major challenges involved in gene prediction involve dealing with sequencing errors in raw DNA data, dependence on the quality of the sequence assembly, handling short reads, frameshift mutations, overlapping genes and incomplete genes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In prokaryotes it's essential to consider horizontal gene transfer when searching for gene sequence homology.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] An additional important factor underused in current gene detection tools is existence of gene clusters — operons (which are functioning units of DNA containing a cluster of genes under the control of a single promoter) in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Most popular gene detectors treat each gene in isolation, independent of others, which is not biologically accurate.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Ab Initio gene prediction is an intrinsic method based on gene content and signal detection.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Because of the inherent expense and difficulty in obtaining extrinsic evidence for many genes, it is also necessary to resort to *ab initio* gene finding, in which the genomic DNA sequence alone is systematically searched for certain tell-tale signs of protein-coding genes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] These signs can be broadly categorized as either *signals*, specific sequences that indicate the presence of a gene nearby, or *content*, statistical properties of the protein-coding sequence itself.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] *Ab initio* gene finding might be more accurately characterized as gene *prediction*, since extrinsic evidence is generally required to conclusively establish that a putative gene is functional.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In the genomes of prokaryotes, genes have specific and relatively well-understood promoter sequences (signals), such as the Pribnow box and transcription factor binding sites, which are easy to systematically identify.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Also, the sequence coding for a protein occurs as one contiguous open reading frame (ORF), which is typically many hundred or thousands of base pairs long.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The statistics of stop codons are such that even finding an open reading frame of this length is a fairly informative sign.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] These characteristics make prokaryotic gene finding relatively straightforward, and well-designed systems are able to achieve high levels of accuracy.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Second, splicing mechanisms employed by eukaryotic cells mean that a particular protein-coding sequence in the genome is divided into several parts (exons), separated by non-coding sequences (introns).
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] (Splice sites are themselves another signal that eukaryotic gene finders are often designed to identify.) A typical protein-coding gene in humans might be divided into a dozen exons, each less than two hundred base pairs in length, and some as short as twenty to thirty.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] It is therefore much more difficult to detect periodicities and other known content properties of protein-coding DNA in eukaryotes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Advanced gene finders for both prokaryotic and eukaryotic genomes typically use complex probabilistic models, such as hidden Markov models (HMMs) to combine information from a variety of different signal and content measurements.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The GLIMMER system is a widely used and highly accurate gene finder for prokaryotes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Eukaryotic *ab initio* gene finders, by comparison, have achieved only limited success; notable examples are the GENSCAN and geneid programs.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The GeneMark-ES and SNAP gene finders are GHMM-based like GENSCAN.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] They attempt to address problems related to using a gene finder on a genome sequence that it was not trained against.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] A few recent approaches like mSplicer, CONTRAST, or mGene also use machine learning techniques like support vector machines for successful gene prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] They build a discriminative model using hidden Markov support vector machines or conditional random fields to learn an accurate gene prediction scoring function.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] It has been suggested that signals other than those directly detectable in sequences may improve gene prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] For example, the role of secondary structure in the identification of regulatory motifs has been reported.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] In addition, it has been suggested that RNA secondary structure prediction helps splice site prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Artificial neural networks are computational models that excel at machine learning and pattern recognition.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Neural networks must be trained with example data before being able to generalise for experimental data, and tested against benchmark data.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Neural networks are able to come up with approximate solutions to problems that are hard to solve algorithmically, provided there is sufficient training data.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] When applied to gene prediction, neural networks can be used alongside other *ab initio* methods to predict or identify biological features such as splice sites.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] One approach involves using a sliding window, which traverses the sequence data in an overlapping manner.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The output at each position is a score based on whether the network thinks the window contains a donor splice site or an acceptor splice site.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Larger windows offer more accuracy but also require more computational power.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] A neural network is an example of a signal sensor as its goal is to identify a functional site in the genome.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Programs such as Maker combine extrinsic and *ab initio* approaches by mapping protein and EST data to the genome to validate *ab initio* predictions.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Augustus, which may be used as part of the Maker pipeline, can also incorporate hints in the form of EST alignments or protein profiles to increase the accuracy of the gene prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] As the entire genomes of many different species are sequenced, a promising direction in current research on gene finding is a comparative genomics approach.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This is based on the principle that the forces of natural selection cause genes and other functional elements to undergo mutation at a slower rate than the rest of the genome, since mutations in functional elements are more likely to negatively impact the organism than mutations elsewhere.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Genes can thus be detected by comparing the genomes of related species to detect this evolutionary pressure for conservation.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This approach was first applied to the mouse and human genomes, using programs such as SLAM, SGP and TWINSCAN/N-SCAN and CONTRAST.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] TWINSCAN examined only human-mouse synteny to look for orthologous genes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Programs such as N-SCAN and CONTRAST allowed the incorporation of alignments from multiple organisms, or in the case of N-SCAN, a single alternate organism from the target.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The use of multiple informants can lead to significant improvements in accuracy.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The first is a smaller classifier, identifying donor splice sites and acceptor splice sites as well as start and stop codons.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The second element involves constructing a full model using machine learning.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Breaking the problem into two means that smaller targeted data sets can be used to train the classifiers, and that classifier can operate independently and be trained with smaller windows.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The full model can use the independent classifier, and not have to waste computational time or model complexity re-classifying intron-exon boundaries.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The paper in which CONTRAST is introduced proposes that their method (and those of TWINSCAN, etc.) be classified as *de novo* gene assembly, using alternate genomes, and identifying it as distinct from *ab initio*, which uses a target 'informant' genomes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Comparative gene finding can also be used to project high quality annotations from one genome to another.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Notable examples include Projector, GeneWise, GeneMapper and GeMoMa.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Such techniques now play a central role in the annotation of all genomes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Pseudogenes are close relatives of genes, sharing very high sequence homology, but being unable to code for the same protein product.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Whilst once relegated as byproducts of gene sequencing, increasingly, as regulatory roles are being uncovered, they are becoming predictive targets in their own right.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Pseudogene prediction utilises existing sequence similarity and ab initio methods, whilst adding additional filtering and methods of identifying pseudogene characteristics.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Sequence similarity methods can be customised for pseudogene prediction using additional filtering to find candidate pseudogenes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This could use disablement detection, which looks for nonsense or frameshift mutations that would truncate or collapse an otherwise functional coding sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Additionally, translating DNA into proteins sequences can be more effective than just straight DNA homology.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Content sensors can be filtered according to the differences in statistical properties between pseudogenes and genes, such as a reduced count of CpG islands in pseudogenes, or the differences in G-C content between pseudogenes and their neighbours.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Signal sensors also can be honed to pseudogenes, looking for the absence of introns or polyadenine tails.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Metagenomics is the study of genetic material recovered from the environment, resulting in sequence information from a pool of organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Predicting genes is useful for comparative metagenomics.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Metagenomics tools also fall into the basic categories of using either sequence similarity approaches (MEGAN4) and ab initio techniques (GLIMMER-MG).
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Glimmer-MG is an extension to GLIMMER that relies mostly on an ab initio approach for gene finding and by using training sets from related organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] The prediction strategy is augmented by classification and clustering gene data sets prior to applying ab initio gene prediction methods.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This classification method leverages techniques from metagenomic phylogenetic classification.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] An example of software for this purpose is, Phymm, which uses interpolated markov models—and PhymmBL, which integrates BLAST into the classification routines.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] MEGAN4 uses a sequence similarity approach, using local alignment against databases of known sequences, but also attempts to classify using additional information on functional roles, biological pathways and enzymes.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] As in single organism gene prediction, sequence similarity approaches are limited by the size of the database.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] FragGeneScan and MetaGeneAnnotator are popular gene prediction programs based on Hidden Markov model.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] These predictors account for sequencing errors, partial genes and work for short reads.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] Another fast and accurate tool for gene prediction in metagenomes is MetaGeneMark.
[src:bioinformatics/gene-prediction] This tool is used by the DOE Joint Genome Institute to annotate IMG/M, the largest metagenome collection to date.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A **phylogenetic tree** or **phylogeny** is a graphical representation which shows the evolutionary history between a set of species or taxa during a specific time.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] In other words, it is a branching diagram or a tree showing the evolutionary relationships among various biological species or other entities based upon similarities and differences in their physical or genetic characteristics.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] In evolutionary biology, all life on Earth is theoretically part of a single phylogenetic tree, indicating common ancestry.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetics is the study of phylogenetic trees.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The main challenge is to find a phylogenetic tree representing optimal evolutionary ancestry between a set of species or taxa.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Computational phylogenetics (also phylogeny inference) focuses on the algorithms involved in finding optimal phylogenetic tree in the phylogenetic landscape.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees may be rooted or unrooted.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] In a *rooted* phylogenetic tree, each node with descendants represents the inferred most recent common ancestor of those descendants, and the edge lengths in some trees may be interpreted as time estimates.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Internal nodes are generally called hypothetical taxonomic units, as they cannot be directly observed.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Trees are useful in fields of biology such as bioinformatics, systematics, and phylogenetics.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] *Unrooted* trees illustrate only the relatedness of the leaf nodes and do not require the ancestral root to be known or inferred.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The idea of a tree of life arose from ancient notions of a ladder-like progression from lower into higher forms of life (such as in the Great Chain of Being).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Early representations of "branching" phylogenetic trees include a "paleontological chart" showing the geological relationships among plants and animals in the book *Elementary Geology*, by Edward Hitchcock (first edition: 1840).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Charles Darwin featured a diagrammatic evolutionary "tree" in his 1859 book *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Over a century later, evolutionary biologists still use tree diagrams to depict evolution because such diagrams effectively convey the concept that speciation occurs through the adaptive and semirandom splitting of lineages.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The term *phylogenetic*, or *phylogeny*, derives from the two ancient greek words φῦλον (*phûlon*), meaning "race, lineage", and γένεσις (*génesis*), meaning "origin, source".
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A rooted phylogenetic tree (see two graphics at top) is a directed tree with a unique node — the root — corresponding to the (usually imputed) most recent common ancestor of all the entities at the leaves of the tree.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The root node does not have a parent node, but serves as the parent of all other nodes in the tree.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The root is therefore a node of degree 2, while other internal nodes have a minimum degree of 3 (where "degree" here refers to the total number of incoming and outgoing edges).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The most common method for rooting trees is the use of an uncontroversial outgroup—close enough to allow inference from trait data or molecular sequencing, but far enough to be a clear outgroup.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Another method is midpoint rooting, or a tree can also be rooted by using a non-stationary substitution model.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Unrooted trees illustrate the relatedness of the leaf nodes without making assumptions about ancestry.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] They do not require the ancestral root to be known or inferred.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Rooted trees can be generated from unrooted ones by inserting a root.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Inferring the root of an unrooted tree requires some means of identifying ancestry.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Both rooted and unrooted trees can be either bifurcating or multifurcating.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A rooted bifurcating tree has exactly two descendants arising from each interior node (that is, it forms a binary tree), and an unrooted bifurcating tree takes the form of an unrooted binary tree, a free tree with exactly three neighbors at each internal node.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] In contrast, a rooted multifurcating tree may have more than two children at some nodes and an unrooted multifurcating tree may have more than three neighbors at some nodes.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Both rooted and unrooted trees can be either labeled or unlabeled.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A labeled tree has specific values assigned to its leaves, while an unlabeled tree, sometimes called a tree shape, defines a topology only.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Some sequence-based trees built from a small genomic locus, such as Phylotree, feature internal nodes labeled with inferred ancestral haplotypes.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The number of possible trees for a given number of leaf nodes depends on the specific type of tree, but there are always more labeled than unlabeled trees, more multifurcating than bifurcating trees, and more rooted than unrooted trees.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The last distinction is the most biologically relevant; it arises because there are many places on an unrooted tree to put the root.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Among labeled bifurcating trees, the number of unrooted trees with n leaves is equal to the number of rooted trees with $n-1$ leaves.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The number of rooted trees grows quickly as a function of the number of tips.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] For 10 tips, there are more than $34\times 10^{6}$ possible bifurcating trees, and the number of multifurcating trees rises faster, with ca.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] 7 times as many of the latter as of the former.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A dendrogram is a general name for a tree, whether phylogenetic or not, and hence also for the diagrammatic representation of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A cladogram only represents a branching pattern; i.e., its branch lengths do not represent time or relative amount of character change, and its internal nodes do not represent ancestors.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A phylogram is a phylogenetic tree that has branch lengths proportional to the amount of character change.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A chronogram is a phylogenetic tree that explicitly represents time through its branch lengths.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A Dahlgrenogram is a diagram representing a cross section of a phylogenetic tree.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A phylogenetic network is not strictly speaking a tree, but rather a more general graph, or a directed acyclic graph in the case of rooted networks.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] They are used to overcome some of the limitations inherent to trees.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A spindle diagram, or bubble diagram, is often called a romerogram, after its popularisation by the American palaeontologist Alfred Romer.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] It represents taxonomic diversity (horizontal width) against geological time (vertical axis) in order to reflect the variation of abundance of various taxa through time.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] A spindle diagram is not an evolutionary tree: the taxonomic spindles obscure the actual relationships of the parent taxon to the daughter taxon and have the disadvantage of involving the paraphyly of the parental group.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] This type of diagram is no longer used in the form originally proposed.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Darwin also mentioned that the *coral* may be a more suitable metaphor than the *tree*.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Indeed, phylogenetic corals are useful for portraying past and present life, and they have some advantages over trees (anastomoses allowed, etc.).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees composed with a nontrivial number of input sequences are constructed using computational phylogenetics methods.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Distance-matrix methods such as neighbor-joining or UPGMA, which calculate genetic distance from multiple sequence alignments, are simplest to implement, but do not invoke an evolutionary model.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Many sequence alignment methods such as ClustalW also create trees by using the simpler algorithms (i.e. those based on distance) of tree construction.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Maximum parsimony is another simple method of estimating phylogenetic trees, but implies an implicit model of evolution (i.e. parsimony).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] More advanced methods use the optimality criterion of maximum likelihood, often within a Bayesian framework, and apply an explicit model of evolution to phylogenetic tree estimation.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Identifying the optimal tree using many of these techniques is NP-hard, so heuristic search and optimization methods are used in combination with tree-scoring functions to identify a reasonably good tree that fits the data.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Tree-building techniques have also gained the attention of mathematicians.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Trees can be encoded in a number of different formats, all of which must represent the nested structure of a tree.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] They may or may not encode branch lengths and other features.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Standardized formats are critical for distributing and sharing trees without relying on graphics output that is hard to import into existing software.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Although phylogenetic trees produced on the basis of sequenced genes or genomic data in different species can provide evolutionary insight, these analyses have important limitations.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Most importantly, the trees that they generate are not necessarily correct – they do not necessarily accurately represent the evolutionary history of the included taxa.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] As with any scientific result, they are subject to falsification by further study (e.g., gathering of additional data, analyzing the existing data with improved methods).
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The data on which they are based may be noisy; the analysis can be confounded by genetic recombination, horizontal gene transfer, hybridisation between species that were not nearest neighbors on the tree before hybridisation takes place, and conserved sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] This is most true of genetic material that is subject to lateral gene transfer and recombination, where different haplotype blocks can have different histories.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] In these types of analysis, the output tree of a phylogenetic analysis of a single gene is an estimate of the gene's phylogeny (i.e. a gene tree) and not the phylogeny of the taxa (i.e. species tree) from which these characters were sampled, though ideally, both should be very close.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] When extinct species are included as terminal nodes in an analysis (rather than, for example, to constrain internal nodes), they are considered not to represent direct ancestors of any extant species.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Extinct species do not typically contain high-quality DNA.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] The range of useful DNA materials has expanded with advances in extraction and sequencing technologies.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Development of technologies able to infer sequences from smaller fragments, or from spatial patterns of DNA degradation products, would further expand the range of DNA considered useful.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic trees can also be inferred from a range of other data types, including morphology, the presence or absence of particular types of genes, insertion and deletion events – and any other observation thought to contain an evolutionary signal.
[src:bioinformatics/phylogenetic-tree] Phylogenetic networks are used when bifurcating trees are not suitable, due to these complications which suggest a more reticulate evolutionary history of the organisms sampled.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure prediction is one of the most important goals pursued by computational biology and addresses Levinthal's paradox.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate structure prediction has important applications in medicine (for example, in drug design) and biotechnology (for example, in novel enzyme design).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Starting in 1994, the performance of current methods is assessed biennially in the *Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction* (CASP) experiment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A continuous evaluation of protein structure prediction web servers is performed by the community project *Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn* (CAMEO3D).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins are chains of amino acids joined together by peptide bonds.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Many conformations of this chain are possible due to the rotation of the main chain about the two torsion angles φ and ψ at the Cα atom.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] This **conformational flexibility** is responsible for differences in the three-dimensional structure of proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The peptide bonds in the chain are polar, i.e. they have separated positive and negative charges (partial charges) in the carbonyl group, which can act as hydrogen bond acceptor and in the NH group, which can act as hydrogen bond donor.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These groups can therefore interact in the protein structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins consist mostly of 20 different types of L-α-amino acids (the proteinogenic amino acids).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These can be classified according to the chemistry of the side chain, which also plays an important structural role.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Glycine takes on a special position, as it has the smallest side chain, only one hydrogen atom, and therefore can increase the local flexibility in the protein structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Cysteine in contrast can react with another cysteine residue to form one cystine and thereby form a cross link stabilizing the whole structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structure arises from a sequence of secondary structure elements, such as α helices and β sheets.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In secondary structures, regular patterns of H-bonds are formed between the main chain NH and CO groups of spatially neighboring amino acids, and the amino acids have similar Φ and ψ angles.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Formation of these secondary structures efficiently satisfies the hydrogen bonding capacities of the peptide bonds.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The secondary structures can be tightly packed in the protein core in a hydrophobic environment, but they can also be present at a polar protein surface.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid side chain has a limited volume to occupy and a limited number of possible interactions with other nearby side chains, a situation that must be taken into account in molecular modeling and alignments.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix is the most abundant type of secondary structure in proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The α-helix has 3.6 amino acids per turn with an H-bond formed between every fourth residue; the average length is 10 amino acids (3 turns) or 10 Å but varies from 5 to 40 (1.5 to 11 turns).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The alignment of the H-bonds creates a dipole moment for the helix with a resulting partial positive charge at the amino end of the helix.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Because this region has free NH2 groups, it will interact with negatively charged groups such as phosphates.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The most common location of α-helices is at the surface of protein cores, where they provide an interface with the aqueous environment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The inner-facing side of the helix tends to have hydrophobic amino acids and the outer-facing side hydrophilic amino acids.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, every third of four amino acids along the chain will tend to be hydrophobic, a pattern that can be quite readily detected.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In the leucine zipper motif, a repeating pattern of leucines on the facing sides of two adjacent helices is highly predictive of the motif.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A helical-wheel plot can be used to show this repeated pattern.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Other α-helices buried in the protein core or in cellular membranes have a higher and more regular distribution of hydrophobic amino acids, and are highly predictive of such structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Helices exposed on the surface have a lower proportion of hydrophobic amino acids.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Amino acid content can be predictive of an α-helical region.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Regions richer in alanine (A), glutamic acid (E), leucine (L), and methionine (M) and poorer in proline (P), glycine (G), tyrosine (Y), and serine (S) tend to form an α-helix.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proline destabilizes or breaks an α-helix but can be present in longer helices, forming a bend.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] β-sheets are formed by H-bonds between an average of 5–10 consecutive amino acids in one portion of the chain with another 5–10 farther down the chain.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The interacting regions may be adjacent, with a short loop in between, or far apart, with other structures in between.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Every chain may run in the same direction to form a parallel sheet, or in the reverse direction to form an antiparallel sheet, or the chains may form a mixed sheet.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern of hydrogen bonding is different in the parallel and antiparallel configurations.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Each amino acid in the interior strands of the sheet forms two H-bonds with neighboring amino acids, whereas each amino acid on the outside strands forms only one bond with an interior strand.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Looking across the sheet at right angles to the strands, more distant strands are rotated slightly counterclockwise to form a left-handed twist.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The Cα-atoms alternate above and below the sheet in a pleated structure, and the R side groups of the amino acids alternate above and below the pleats.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The Φ and Ψ angles of the amino acids in sheets vary considerably in one region of the Ramachandran plot.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] It is more difficult to predict the location of β-sheets than of α-helices.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The situation improves somewhat when the amino acid variation in multiple sequence alignments is taken into account.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Parts of the protein may have fixed three-dimensional structure without regular structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] They should not be confused with disordered or unfolded segments of proteins or random coil, an unfolded polypeptide chain lacking any fixed three-dimensional structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These parts are frequently called "deltas" (*Δ*) because they connect β-sheets and α-helices.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas are usually located at protein surface, and therefore mutations of their residues are more easily tolerated.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Having more substitutions, insertions, and deletions in a certain region of a sequence alignment maybe an indication of some delta.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The positions of introns in genomic DNA may correlate with the locations of loops in the encoded protein .
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Deltas also tend to have charged and polar amino acids and are frequently a component of active sites.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins may be classified according to both structural and sequential similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] For structural classification, the sizes and spatial arrangements of secondary structures described in the above paragraph are compared in known three-dimensional structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Classification based on sequence similarity was historically the first to be used.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Initially, similarity based on alignments of whole sequences was performed.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Later, proteins were classified on the basis of the occurrence of conserved amino acid patterns.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Databases that classify proteins by one or more of these schemes are available.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In considering protein classification schemes, it is important to keep several observations in mind.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] First, two entirely different protein sequences from different evolutionary origins may fold into a similar structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Conversely, the sequence of an ancient gene for a given structure may have diverged considerably in different species while at the same time maintaining the same basic structural features.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Recognizing any remaining sequence similarity in such cases may be a very difficult task.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Second, two proteins that share a significant degree of sequence similarity either with each other or with a third sequence also share an evolutionary origin and should share some structural features also.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] However, gene duplication and genetic rearrangements during evolution may give rise to new gene copies, which can then evolve into proteins with new function and structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The more commonly used terms for evolutionary and structural relationships among proteins are listed below.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Many additional terms are used for various kinds of structural features found in proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Descriptions of such terms may be found at the CATH Web site, the Structural Classification of Proteins (SCOP) Web site, and a Glaxo Wellcome tutorial on the Swiss bioinformatics Expasy Web site.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a localized combination of amino acid side groups within the tertiary (three-dimensional) or quaternary (protein subunit) structure that can interact with a chemically specific substrate and that provides the protein with biological activity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins of very different amino acid sequences may fold into a structure that produces the same active site.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] is the relative orientations of secondary structures in a three-dimensional structure without regard to whether or not they share a similar loop structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a type of architecture that also has a conserved loop structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] is a conserved amino acid sequence pattern in a family of proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The pattern includes a series of possible matches at each position in the represented sequences, but there are not any inserted or deleted positions in the pattern or in the sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] By way of contrast, sequence profiles are a type of scoring matrix that represents a similar set of patterns that includes insertions and deletions.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a term used to classify protein domains according to their secondary structural content and organization.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] were originally recognized by Levitt and Chothia (1976), and several others have been added in the SCOP database.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Three classes are given in the CATH database: mainly-α, mainly-β, and α–β, with the α–β class including both alternating α/β and α+β structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] the portion of a folded protein molecule that comprises the hydrophobic interior of α-helices and β-sheets.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The compact structure brings together side groups of amino acids into close enough proximity so that they can interact.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] When comparing protein structures, as in the SCOP database, core is the region common to most of the structures that share a common fold or that are in the same superfamily.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In structure prediction, core is sometimes defined as the arrangement of secondary structures that is likely to be conserved during evolutionary change.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a segment of a polypeptide chain that can fold into a three-dimensional structure irrespective of the presence of other segments of the chain.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The separate domains of a given protein may interact extensively or may be joined only by a length of polypeptide chain.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A protein with several domains may use these domains for functional interactions with different molecules.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a group of proteins of similar biochemical function that are more than 50% identical when aligned.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A protein family comprises proteins with the same function in different organisms (orthologous sequences) but may also include proteins in the same organism (paralogous sequences) derived from gene duplication and rearrangements.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] If a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family reveals a common level of similarity throughout the lengths of the proteins, PIR refers to the family as a homeomorphic family.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The aligned region is referred to as a homeomorphic domain, and this region may comprise several smaller homology domains that are shared with other families.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Families may be further subdivided into subfamilies or grouped into superfamilies based on respective higher or lower levels of sequence similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The SCOP database reports 1296 families and the CATH database (version 1.7 beta), reports 1846 families.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] When the sequences of proteins with the same function are examined in greater detail, some are found to share high sequence similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] They are obviously members of the same family by the above criteria.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] However, others are found that have very little, or even insignificant, sequence similarity with other family members.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In such cases, the family relationship between two distant family members A and C can often be demonstrated by finding an additional family member B that shares significant similarity with both A and C.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, B provides a connecting link between A and C.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Another approach is to examine distant alignments for highly conserved matches.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] At a level of identity of 50%, proteins are likely to have the same three-dimensional structure, and the identical atoms in the sequence alignment will also superimpose within approximately 1 Å in the structural model.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, if the structure of one member of a family is known, a reliable prediction may be made for a second member of the family, and the higher the identity level, the more reliable the prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Protein structural modeling can be performed by examining how well the amino acid substitutions fit into the core of the three-dimensional structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] ) and the DALI/FSSP Web site, two structures that have a significant level of structural similarity but not necessarily significant sequence similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] similar to structural motif, includes a larger combination of secondary structural units in the same configuration.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Thus, proteins sharing the same fold have the same combination of secondary structures that are connected by similar loops.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the Rossman fold comprising several alternating α helices and parallel β strands.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In the SCOP, CATH, and FSSP databases, the known protein structures have been classified into hierarchical levels of structural complexity with the fold as a basic level of classification.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] an extended sequence pattern, generally found by sequence alignment methods, that indicates a common evolutionary origin among the aligned sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A homology domain is generally longer than motifs.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The domain may include all of a given protein sequence or only a portion of the sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Some domains are complex and made up of several smaller homology domains that became joined to form a larger one during evolution.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a region of conserved amino acid patterns comprising one or more motifs and considered to be a fundamental unit of structure or function.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The presence of a module has also been used to classify proteins into families.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a conserved pattern of amino acids that is found in two or more proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] catalog, a motif is an amino acid pattern that is found in a group of proteins that have a similar biochemical activity, and that often is near the active site of the protein.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Examples of sequence motif databases are the Prosite catalog and the Stanford Motifs Database.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a combination of several secondary structural elements produced by the folding of adjacent sections of the polypeptide chain into a specific three-dimensional configuration.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] An example is the helix-loop-helix motif.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Structural motifs are also referred to as supersecondary structures and folds.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] represents a conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment with no gaps.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Each matrix column represents the variation found in one column of the multiple sequence alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] represents the amino acid variation found in an alignment of proteins that fall into the same structural class.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix columns represent the amino acid variation found at one amino acid position in the aligned structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] the linear amino acid sequence of a protein, which chemically is a polypeptide chain composed of amino acids joined by peptide bonds.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents a multiple sequence alignment of a protein family.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is usually obtained from a well-conserved region in a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is in the form of a matrix with each column representing a position in the alignment and each row one of the amino acids.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Matrix values give the likelihood of each amino acid at the corresponding position in the alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The profile is moved along the target sequence to locate the best scoring regions by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps are allowed during matching and a gap penalty is included in this case as a negative score when no amino acid is matched.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a scoring matrix that represents which amino acids should fit well and which should fit poorly at sequential positions in a known protein structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Profile columns represent sequential positions in the structure, and profile rows represent the 20 amino acids.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] As with a sequence profile, the structural profile is moved along a target sequence to find the highest possible alignment score by a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Gaps may be included and receive a penalty.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The resulting score provides an indication as to whether or not the target protein might adopt such a structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] the three-dimensional configuration of a protein molecule comprising several independent polypeptide chains.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] the interactions that occur between the C, O, and NH groups on amino acids in a polypeptide chain to form α-helices, β-sheets, turns, loops, and other forms, and that facilitate the folding into a three-dimensional structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a group of protein families of the same or different lengths that are related by distant yet detectable sequence similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Originally, Dayhoff defined the cutoff for superfamily status as being the chance that the sequences are not related of 10 6, on the basis of an alignment score (Dayhoff et al.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Proteins with few identities in an alignment of the sequences but with a convincingly common number of structural and functional features are placed in the same superfamily.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] At the level of three-dimensional structure, superfamily proteins will share common structural features such as a common fold, but there may also be differences in the number and arrangement of secondary structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] to refer to superfamilies that are composed of sequences that can be aligned from end to end, representing a sharing of single sequence homology domain, a region of similarity that extends throughout the alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] This domain may also comprise smaller homology domains that are shared with other protein families and superfamilies.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Although a given protein sequence may contain domains found in several superfamilies, thus indicating a complex evolutionary history, sequences will be assigned to only one homeomorphic superfamily based on the presence of similarity throughout a multiple sequence alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The superfamily alignment may also include regions that do not align either within or at the ends of the alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, sequences in the same family align well throughout the alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] a term with similar meaning to a structural motif.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Tertiary structure is the three-dimensional or globular structure formed by the packing together or folding of secondary structures of a polypeptide chain.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of current protein secondary structure prediction methods is assessed in weekly benchmarks such as LiveBench and EVA.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Early methods of secondary structure prediction, introduced in the 1960s and early 1970s, focused on identifying likely alpha helices and were based mainly on helix-coil transition models.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Significantly more accurate predictions that included beta sheets were introduced in the 1970s and relied on statistical assessments based on probability parameters derived from known solved structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These methods, applied to a single sequence, are typically at most about 60–65% accurate, and often underpredict beta sheets.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Since the 1980s, artificial neural networks have been applied to the prediction of protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The evolutionary conservation of secondary structures can be exploited by simultaneously assessing many homologous sequences in a multiple sequence alignment, by calculating the net secondary structure propensity of an aligned column of amino acids.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In concert with larger databases of known protein structures and modern machine learning methods such as neural nets and support vector machines, these methods can achieve up to 80% overall accuracy in globular proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The theoretical upper limit of accuracy is around 90%, partly due to idiosyncrasies in DSSP assignment near the ends of secondary structures, where local conformations vary under native conditions but may be forced to assume a single conformation in crystals due to packing constraints.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Dramatic conformational changes related to the protein's function or environment can also alter local secondary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] To date, over 20 different secondary structure prediction methods have been developed.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] One of the first algorithms was Chou–Fasman method, which relies predominantly on probability parameters determined from relative frequencies of each amino acid's appearance in each type of secondary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The original Chou-Fasman parameters, determined from the small sample of structures solved in the mid-1970s, produce poor results compared to modern methods, though the parameterization has been updated since it was first published.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The Chou-Fasman method is roughly 50–60% accurate in predicting secondary structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The next notable program was the GOR method is an information theory-based method.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] It uses the more powerful probabilistic technique of Bayesian inference.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The approach is both more sensitive and more accurate than that of Chou and Fasman because amino acid structural propensities are only strong for a small number of amino acids such as proline and glycine.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Weak contributions from each of many neighbors can add up to strong effects overall.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The original GOR method was roughly 65% accurate and is dramatically more successful in predicting alpha helices than beta sheets, which it frequently mispredicted as loops or disorganized regions.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Another big step forward was using machine learning methods.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] First artificial neural networks methods were used.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] As a training sets they use solved structures to identify common sequence motifs associated with particular arrangements of secondary structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] PSIPRED and JPRED are some of the most known programs based on neural networks for protein secondary structure prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Next, support vector machines have proven particularly useful for predicting the locations of turns, which are difficult to identify with statistical methods.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Extensions of machine learning techniques attempt to predict more fine-grained local properties of proteins, such as backbone dihedral angles in unassigned regions.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Both SVMs and neural networks have been applied to this problem.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] More recently, real-value torsion angles can be accurately predicted by SPINE-X and successfully employed for ab initio structure prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] It is reported that in addition to the protein sequence, secondary structure formation depends on other factors.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] For example, it is reported that secondary structure tendencies depend also on local environment, solvent accessibility of residues, protein structural class, and even the organism from which the proteins are obtained.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Based on such observations, some studies have shown that secondary structure prediction can be improved by addition of information about protein structural class, residue accessible surface area and also contact number information.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The practical role of protein structure prediction is now more important than ever.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Massive amounts of protein sequence data are produced by modern large-scale DNA sequencing efforts such as the Human Genome Project.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Despite community-wide efforts in structural genomics, the output of experimentally determined protein structures—typically by time-consuming and relatively expensive X-ray crystallography or NMR spectroscopy—is lagging far behind the output of protein sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The protein structure prediction remains an extremely difficult and unresolved undertaking.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The two main problems are the calculation of protein free energy and finding the global minimum of this energy.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A protein structure prediction method must explore the space of possible protein structures which is astronomically large.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These problems can be partially bypassed in "comparative" or homology modeling and fold recognition methods, in which the search space is pruned by the assumption that the protein in question adopts a structure that is close to the experimentally determined structure of another homologous protein.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In contrast, the de novo protein structure prediction methods must explicitly resolve these problems.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The progress and challenges in protein structure prediction have been reviewed by Zhang.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Most tertiary structure modelling methods, such as Rosetta, are optimized for modelling the tertiary structure of single protein domains.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A step called **domain parsing**, or **domain boundary prediction**, is usually done first to split a protein into potential structural domains.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] As with the rest of tertiary structure prediction, this can be done comparatively from known structures or *ab initio* with the sequence only (usually by machine learning, assisted by covariation).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The structures for individual domains are docked together in a process called **domain assembly** to form the final tertiary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2009, a 50-residue protein could be simulated atom-by-atom on a supercomputer for 1 millisecond.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] As of 2012, comparable stable-state sampling could be done on a standard desktop with a new graphics card and more sophisticated algorithms.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A much larger simulation timescales can be achieved using coarse-grained modeling.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The assumption is when single residue mutations are slightly deleterious, compensatory mutations may occur to restabilize residue-residue interactions.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] This early work used what are known as *local* methods to calculate correlated mutations from protein sequences, but suffered from indirect false correlations which result from treating each pair of residues as independent of all other pairs.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In 2011, a different, and this time *global* statistical approach, demonstrated that predicted coevolved residues were sufficient to predict the 3D fold of a protein, providing there are enough sequences available (>1,000 homologous sequences are needed).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The method, EVfold, uses no homology modeling, threading or 3D structure fragments and can be run on a standard personal computer even for proteins with hundreds of residues.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The accuracy of the contacts predicted using this and related approaches has now been demonstrated on many known structures and contact maps, including the prediction of experimentally unsolved transmembrane proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Comparative protein modeling uses previously solved structures as starting points, or templates.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] This is effective because it appears that although the number of actual proteins is vast, there is a limited set of tertiary structural motifs to which most proteins belong.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] It has been suggested that there are only around 2,000 distinct protein folds in nature, though there are many millions of different proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The comparative protein modeling can combine with the evolutionary covariation in the structure prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Accurate packing of the amino acid side chains represents a separate problem in protein structure prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Methods that specifically address the problem of predicting side-chain geometry include dead-end elimination and the self-consistent mean field methods.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The side chain conformations with low energy are usually determined on the rigid polypeptide backbone and using a set of discrete side chain conformations known as "rotamers".
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The methods attempt to identify the set of rotamers that minimize the model's overall energy.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] These methods use rotamer libraries, which are collections of favorable conformations for each residue type in proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries may contain information about the conformation, its frequency, and the standard deviations about mean dihedral angles, which can be used in sampling.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries are derived from structural bioinformatics or other statistical analysis of side-chain conformations in known experimental structures of proteins, such as by clustering the observed conformations for tetrahedral carbons near the staggered (60°, 180°, −60°) values.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Rotamer libraries can be backbone-independent, secondary-structure-dependent, or backbone-dependent.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-independent rotamer libraries make no reference to backbone conformation, and are calculated from all available side chains of a certain type (for instance, the first example of a rotamer library, done by Ponder and Richards at Yale in 1987).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Secondary-structure-dependent libraries present different dihedral angles and/or rotamer frequencies for $\alpha$ -helix, $\beta$ -sheet, or coil secondary structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Backbone-dependent rotamer libraries present conformations and/or frequencies dependent on the local backbone conformation as defined by the backbone dihedral angles $\phi$ and $\psi$ , regardless of secondary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The modern versions of these libraries as used in most software are presented as multidimensional distributions of probability or frequency, where the peaks correspond to the dihedral-angle conformations considered as individual rotamers in the lists.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Some versions are based on very carefully curated data and are used primarily for structure validation, while others emphasize relative frequencies in much larger data sets and are the form used primarily for structure prediction, such as the Dunbrack rotamer libraries.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In the case of complexes of two or more proteins, where the structures of the proteins are known or can be predicted with high accuracy, protein–protein docking methods can be used to predict the structure of the complex.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Information of the effect of mutations at specific sites on the affinity of the complex helps to understand the complex structure and to guide docking methods.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] A great number of software tools for protein structure prediction exist.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Approaches include homology modeling, protein threading, *ab initio* methods, secondary structure prediction, and transmembrane helix and signal peptide prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In particular, deep learning based on long short-term memory has been used for this purpose since 2007, when it was successfully applied to protein homology detection and to predict subcellular localization of proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Some recent successful methods based on the CASP experiments include I-TASSER, HHpred and AlphaFold.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In 2021, AlphaFold was reported to perform best.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Knowing the structure of a protein often allows functional prediction as well.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] For instance, collagen is folded into a long-extended fiber-like chain and it makes it a fibrous protein.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Recently, several techniques have been developed to predict protein folding and thus protein structure, for example, Itasser, and AlphaFold.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was one of the first AIs to predict protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] It was introduced by Google's DeepMind in the 13th CASP competition, which was held in 2018.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold relies on a neural network approach, which directly predicts the 3D coordinates of all non-hydrogen atoms for a given protein using the amino acid sequence and aligned homologous sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The AlphaFold network consists of a trunk which processes the inputs through repeated layers, and a structure module which introduces an explicit 3D structure.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Earlier neural networks for protein structure prediction used LSTM.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Since AlphaFold outputs protein coordinates directly, AlphaFold produces predictions in graphics processing unit (GPU) minutes to GPU hours, depending on the length of protein sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The European Bioinformatics Institute together with DeepMind have constructed the AlphaFold – EBI database for predicted protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2, was introduced in CASP14, and is capable of predicting protein structures to near experimental accuracy.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold was swiftly followed by RoseTTAFold and later by OmegaFold and the ESM Metagenomic Atlas.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] 2022 demonstrated the application of protein structure prediction in genome annotation, specifically in identifying functional protein isoforms using computationally predicted structures, available at https://www.isoform.io.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] This study highlights the promise of protein structure prediction as a genome annotation tool and presents a practical, structure-guided approach that can be used to enhance the annotation of any genome.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In 2024, David Baker and Demis Hassabis (along with John M.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Jumper) were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their contributions to computational protein modeling, including the development of AlphaFold2, an AI-based model for protein structure prediction.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] AlphaFold2's accuracy has been evaluated against experimentally determined protein structures using metrics such as root-mean-square deviation (RMSD).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The median RMSD between different experimental structures of the same protein is approximately 0.6 Å, while the median RMSD between AlphaFold2 predictions and experimental structures is around 1 Å.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] For regions where AlphaFold2 assigns high confidence, the median RMSD is about 0.6 Å, comparable to the variability observed between different experimental structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] However, in low-confidence regions, the RMSD can exceed 2 Å, indicating greater deviations.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] In proteins with multiple domains connected by flexible linkers, AlphaFold2 predicts individual domain structures accurately but may assign random relative positions to these domains.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] Additionally, AlphaFold2 does not account for structural constraints such as the membrane plane, sometimes placing protein domains in positions that would physically clash with the membrane.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] CASP, which stands for Critical Assessment of Techniques for Protein Structure Prediction, is a community-wide experiment for protein structure prediction taking place every two years since 1994.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] CASP provides with an opportunity to assess the quality of available human, non-automated methodology (human category) and automatic servers for protein structure prediction (server category, introduced in the CASP7).
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] The CAMEO3D Continuous Automated Model EvaluatiOn Server evaluates automated protein structure prediction servers on a weekly basis using blind predictions for newly release protein structures.
[src:bioinformatics/protein-structure-prediction] CAMEO publishes the results on its website.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In bioinformatics, **sequence analysis** is the process of subjecting a DNA, RNA or peptide sequence to any of a wide range of analytical methods to understand its features, function, structure, or evolution.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It can be performed on the entire genome, transcriptome or proteome of an organism, and can also involve only selected segments or regions, like tandem repeats and transposable elements.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Methodologies used include sequence alignment, searches against biological databases, and others.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Since the development of methods of high-throughput production of gene and protein sequences, the rate of addition of new sequences to the databases increased very rapidly.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Such a collection of sequences does not, by itself, increase the scientist's understanding of the biology of organisms.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] However, comparing these new sequences to those with known functions is a key way of understanding the biology of an organism from which the new sequence comes.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Thus, sequence analysis can be used to assign function to coding and non-coding regions in a biological sequence usually by comparing sequences and studying similarities and differences.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Identification of sequence differences and variations such as point mutations and single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) in order to get the genetic marker.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Identification of molecular structure from sequence alone.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Since the very first sequences of the insulin protein were characterized by Fred Sanger in 1951, biologists have been trying to use this knowledge to understand the function of molecules.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] He and his colleagues' discoveries contributed to the successful sequencing of the first DNA-based genome.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The method used in this study, which is called the "Sanger method" or Sanger sequencing, was a milestone in sequencing long strand molecules such as DNA.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This method was eventually used in the Human Genome Project.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] According to Michael Levitt, sequence analysis was born in the period from 1969 to 1977.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In 1969 the analysis of sequences of transfer RNAs was used to infer residue interactions from correlated changes in the nucleotide sequences, giving rise to a model of the tRNA secondary structure.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Wunsch published the first computer algorithm for aligning two sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Over this time, developments in obtaining nucleotide sequence improved greatly, leading to the publication of the first complete genome of a bacteriophage in 1977.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Robert Holley and his team in Cornell University were believed to be the first to sequence an RNA molecule.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Nucleotide sequence analyses identify functional elements like protein binding sites, uncover genetic variations like SNPs, study gene expression patterns, and understand the genetic basis of traits.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It helps to understand mechanisms that contribute to processes like replication and transcription.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Some of the tasks involved are outlined below.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Quality control assesses the quality of sequencing reads obtained from the sequencing technology (e.g.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It is the first step in sequence analysis to limit wrong conclusions due to poor quality data.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The tools used at this stage depend on the sequencing platform.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] For instance, FastQC checks the quality of short reads (including RNA sequences), Nanoplot or PycoQC are used for long read sequences (e.g.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Nanopore sequence reads), and MultiQC aggregates the result of FastQC in a webpage format.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Quality control provides information such as read lengths, GC content, presence of adapter sequences (for short reads), and a quality score, which is often expressed on a PHRED scale.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] If adapters or other artifacts from PCR amplification are present in the reads (particularly short reads), they are removed using software such as Trimmomatic or Cutadapt.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] At this step, sequencing reads whose quality have been improved are mapped to a reference genome using alignment tools like BWA for short DNA sequence reads, minimap for long read DNA sequences, and STAR for RNA sequence reads.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The purpose of mapping is to find the origin of any given read based on the reference sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It is also important for detecting variations or phylogenetic studies.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The output from this step, that is, the aligned reads, are stored in compatible file formats known as SAM, which contains information about the reference genome as well as individual reads.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Alternatively, BAM file formats are preferred as they use much less desk or storage space.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Identifying variants is a popular aspect of sequence analysis as variants often contain information of biological significance, such as explaining the mechanism of drug resistance in an infectious disease.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These variants could be single nucleotide variants (SNVs), small insertions/deletions (indels), and large structural variants.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The read alignments are sorted using SAMtools, after which variant callers such as GATK are used to identify differences compared to the reference sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The choice of variant calling tool depends heavily on the sequencing technology used, so GATK is often used when working with short reads, while long read sequences require tools like DeepVariant and Sniffles.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Tools may also differ based on organism (prokaryotes or eukaryotes), source of sequence data (cancer vs metagenomic), and variant type of interest (SNVs or structural variants).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The output of variant calling is typically in vcf format, and can be filtered using allele frequencies, quality scores, or other factors based on the research question at hand.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This step adds context to the variant data using curated information from peer-reviewed papers and publicly available databases like gnomAD and Ensembl.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Variants can be annotated with information about genomic features, functional consequences, regulatory elements, and population frequencies using tools like ANNOVAR or SnpEff, or custom scripts and pipeline.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The output from this step is an annotation file in bed or txt format.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Genomic data, such as read alignments, coverage plots, and variant calls, can be visualized using genome browsers like IGV (Integrative Genomics Viewer) or UCSC Genome Browser.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Interpretation of the results is done in the context of the biological question or hypothesis under investigation.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The output can be a graphical representation of data in the forms of Circos plots, volcano plots, etc., or other forms of report describing the observations.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] DNA sequence analysis could also involve statistical modeling to infer relationships and epigenetic analysis, like identifying differential methylation regions using a tool like DSS.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Mapped RNA sequences are analyzed to estimate gene expression levels using quantification tools such as HTSeq, and identify differentially expressed genes (DEGs) between experimental conditions using statistical methods like DESeq2.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This is carried out to compare the expression levels of genes or isoforms between or across different samples, and infer biological relevance.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The output of gene expression analysis is typically a table with values representing the expression levels of gene IDs or names in rows and samples in the columns as well as standard errors and p-values.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The results in the table can be further visualized using volcano plots and heatmaps, where colors represent the estimated expression level.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Packages like ggplot2 in R and Matplotlib in Python are often used to create the visuals.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The table can also be annotated using a reference annotation file, usually in GTF or GFF format to provide more context about the genes, such as the chromosome name, strand, and start and positions, and aid result interpretation.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Functional enrichment analysis identifies biological processes, pathways, and functional impacts associated with differentially expressed genes obtained from the previous step.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This creates a table with information about what pathways and molecular processes are associated with the differentially expressed genes, what genes are down or upregulated, and what gene ontology terms are recurrent or over-represented.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] RNA sequence analysis explores gene expression dynamics and regulatory mechanisms underlying biological processes and diseases.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Interpretation of images and tables are carried out within the context of the hypotheses being investigated.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Proteome sequence analysis studies the complete set of proteins expressed by an organism or a cell under specific conditions.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It describes protein structure, function, post-translational modifications, and interactions within biological systems.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It often starts with raw mass spectrometry (MS) data from proteomics experiments, typically in mzML, mzXML, or RAW file formats.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The choice and order of analytical steps depend on the MS method used, which can either be data dependent acquisition (DDA) or independent acquisition (DIA).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Genome browsers offer a non-code, user-friendly interface to visualize genomes and genomic segments, identify genomic features, and analyze the relationship between numerous genomic elements.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] All browsers support multiple data formats for upload and download and provide links to external tools and resources for sequence analyses, which contributes to their versatility.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] There are millions of protein and nucleotide sequences known.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These sequences fall into many groups of related sequences known as protein families or gene families.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Relationships between these sequences are usually discovered by aligning them together and assigning this alignment a score.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] There are two main types of sequence alignment.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Pair-wise sequence alignment only compares two sequences at a time and multiple sequence alignment compares many sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Two important algorithms for aligning pairs of sequences are the Needleman-Wunsch algorithm and the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] A common use for pairwise sequence alignment is to take a sequence of interest and compare it to all known sequences in a database to identify homologous sequences.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In general, the matches in the database are ordered to show the most closely related sequences first, followed by sequences with diminishing similarity.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These matches are usually reported with a measure of statistical significance such as an Expectation value.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In 1987, Michael Gribskov, Andrew McLachlan, and David Eisenberg introduced the method of profile comparison for identifying distant similarities between proteins.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Rather than using a single sequence, profile methods use a multiple sequence alignment to encode a profile which contains information about the conservation level of each residue.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These profiles can then be used to search collections of sequences to find sequences that are related.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Profiles are also known as Position Specific Scoring Matrices (PSSMs).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In 1993, a probabilistic interpretation of profiles was introduced by Anders Krogh and colleagues using hidden Markov models.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These models have become known as profile-HMMs.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In recent years, methods have been developed that allow the comparison of profiles directly to each other.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] These are known as profile-profile comparison methods.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Sequence assembly refers to the reconstruction of a DNA sequence by aligning and merging small DNA fragments.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] It is an integral part of modern DNA sequencing.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Recently, sequencing multiple species at one time is one of the top research objectives.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Metagenomics is the study of microbial communities directly obtained from the environment.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Different from cultured microorganisms from the lab, the wild sample usually contains dozens, sometimes even thousands of types of microorganisms from their original habitats.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Recovering the original genomes can prove to be very challenging.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Gene prediction or gene finding refers to the process of identifying the regions of genomic DNA that encode genes.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This includes protein-coding genes as well as RNA genes, but may also include the prediction of other functional elements such as regulatory regions.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Geri is one of the first and most important steps in understanding the genome of a species once it has been sequenced.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In general, the prediction of bacterial genes is significantly simpler and more accurate than the prediction of genes in eukaryotic species that usually have complex intron/exon patterns.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Identifying genes in long sequences remains a problem, especially when the number of genes is unknown.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Hidden markov models can be part of the solution.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Machine learning has played a significant role in predicting the sequence of transcription factors.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Traditional sequencing analysis focused on the statistical parameters of the nucleotide sequence itself (The most common programs used are listed in Table 4.1).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Another method is to identify homologous sequences based on other known gene sequences (Tools see Table 4.3).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The two methods described here are focused on the sequence.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] However, the shape feature of these molecules such as DNA and protein have also been studied and proposed to have an equivalent, if not higher, influence on the behaviors of these molecules.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] The 3D structures of molecules are of major importance to their functions in nature.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Since structural prediction of large molecules at an atomic level is a largely intractable problem, some biologists introduced ways to predict 3D structure at a primary sequence level.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] This includes the biochemical or statistical analysis of amino acid residues in local regions and structural the inference from homologs (or other potentially related proteins) with known 3D structures.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] There have been a large number of diverse approaches to solve the structure prediction problem.
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] In order to determine which methods were most effective, a structure prediction competition was founded called CASP (Critical Assessment of Structure Prediction).
[src:bioinformatics/sequence-analysis] Sequence analysis tasks are often non-trivial to resolve and require the use of relatively complex approaches, many of which are the backbone behind many existing sequence analysis tools.
